SwZTJ FGwzt ukgoS</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">yCeTE</span>"&gt;</span>Photo Worthy Transportaion Hub and Shopping Complex with Stunning Architecture<span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/a&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">_T FKffI bmUTE</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">fIrGe _T bgMZj</span>" <span class="html-attribute-name">style</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">-webkit-line-clamp:7;line-break:normal;cursor:pointer</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">biGQs _P pZUbB KxBGd</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">JguWG</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">yCeTE</span>"&gt;</span>Incredible architecture inside this multi-purpose building at the World Trade Center complex and includes a high-end mall but also serves as a transportation hub including the NYC subway and PATH trains to New Jersey.  This is a photo worthy stop if coming to Lower Manhattan to visit the 9/11 Memorial or the One World Observation Deck. Quite amazingly, the structure's orientation serves as a lasting reminder of the attacks of September 11, 2001. It is in alignment with the suns solar angles on each September 11, from 8:46 am, when the first plane struck, until 10:28 am, when the second tower collapsed. Its central skylight fits this alignment and washes the Oculus floor with a beam of light.<span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-attribute-value">translate(104 0)</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/path&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/svg&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">biGQs _P fiohW qWPrE ncFvv fOtGX</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;a <span class="html-attribute-name">target</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">_blank</span>" <span class="html-attribute-name">tabindex</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">0</span>" <span class="html-attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="html-attribute-value html-external-link" target="_blank" href="https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g60763-d104370-r944172190-Ellis_Island-New_York_City_New_York.html" rel="noreferrer noopener">/ShowUserReviews-g60763-d104370-r944172190-Ellis_Island-New_York_City_New_York.html</a>" <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">BMQDV _F Gv wSSLS SwZTJ FGwzt ukgoS</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">yCeTE</span>"&gt;</span>Historical - must see in New York<span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/a&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">_T FKffI bmUTE</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">fIrGe _T bgMZj</span>" <span class="html-attribute-name">style</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">-webkit-line-clamp:7;line-break:normal;cursor:pointer</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">biGQs _P pZUbB KxBGd</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">JguWG</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">yCeTE</span>"&gt;</span>Ellis Island, located in New York Harbor near the Statue of Liberty, served as the United States' largest immigration station from 1892 to 1954. Named after its 18th-century owner, Samuel Ellis, the island was expanded over time by landfills.<span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span>Before it became an immigration station, Ellis Island was used for various purposes by the U.S. government, such as serving as a munitions arsenal during the War of 1812. The federal government bought the island in 1808 and it was used as a fort during the Civil War.<span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span>On January 1, 1892, Ellis Island replaced Castle Garden (located in Battery Park, Manhattan) as the main immigration center for the United States. The first immigrant to pass through Ellis Island was Annie Moore, a 15-year-old girl from Ireland who arrived with her two younger brothers to join their parents in New York City.<span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span>From 1892 to 1924, more than 12 million immigrants passed through Ellis Island in search of a better life in America. Most of these immigrants were from Europe, escaping poverty, religious persecution, and political unrest.<span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span>The processing of immigrants at Ellis Island involved a series of medical and legal inspections to determine if they were fit for entry into the United States. Those who failed these inspections could be sent back to their home countries.<span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span>In 1924, the Immigration Act was passed, which greatly reduced the number of immigrants allowed entry into the United States and effectively ended mass immigration to America. After this, Ellis Island was mainly used as a detention and deportation center for immigrants.<span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;br /&gt;</span>The island was closed as an immigration center in 1954 and declared surplus federal property. It was neglected for many years until it was restored and turned into a museum and national monument. The Ellis Island National Museum of Immigration opened in 1990 and today, it attracts millions of visitors each year who come to explore the history of American immigration.<span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">lszDU</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;button <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">UikNM _G B- _S _W _T c G_ wSSLS wnNQG</span>" <span class="html-attribute-name">type</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">button</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;span <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">biGQs _P XWJSj Wb</span>"&gt;</span>Read more<span class="html-tag">&lt;/span&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;div <span class="html-attribute-name">class</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">CECjK _W</span>"&gt;</span><span class="html-tag">&lt;svg <span class="html-attribute-name">viewBox</span>="<span class="html-attribute-value">0 0 24 24</span>" <span class="html-attribute-name">width</span>="<span
